04591nam a22005055i 9780773568440DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20012001xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735684407 a10.1515/97807735684402doi  a(DE-B1597)654983  a(OCoLC)1394871847  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHE7814 ǂb R4513 2001eb 7aTEC0410002bisacsh04a384/.09711 aRens, Jean-Guy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInvisible Empire :bA History of the telecommunications industry in Canada, 1846-1956 /cJean-Guy Rens. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tThe Pioneering Era: Inventions and Impediments, 1846–1915 -- tTelegraphy -- tThe Birth of Telegraphy -- tThe Telegraph Industry Gets Organized -- tThe Telephone -- tInvention of the Telephone -- tThe Telephone Comes to Canada -- tBell Comes Out Fighting -- tBalkanization of the Telephone Industry -- tThe Birth of Northern Electric and Technological Advances -- tUnbridled Capitalism and Language Clashes -- tThe Telephone Industry in Canada and the International Scene -- tRadio -- tRadio: A Spectacular Success -- tCreating Universal Service, 1915–56 -- tCreation of a National Industry -- tBell’s Long March to Independence -- tThe Other Telephone Companies -- tSocial Benefits and Labour Peace in the Telephone Industry -- tThe Canadian Regulatory Model -- tElectromechanical Technology Hits Its Peak -- tThe International Scene -- tConclusion: How Telephony Changed the World -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is impossible to understand Canada without looking at the history and development of its telecommunications industry. In the nineteenth century Canada was the only country in the world constructed on the basis of technology - first the railway and, in its shadow, telegraphy. In the 1930s this technological nationalism came of age and telecommunications became Canada's "national" technology. The Invisible Empire provides the first overview of Canadian telecommunications, from the laying of the first telegraph line between Toronto and Hamilton in 1846 to the separation between Nortel - then known as Northern Electric - and the American Bell System in 1956. Rens shows us that Louis Riel was beaten as much by telegraphy as by the Canadian army, and how Bell Canada - then known as Bell Telephone - escaped nationalization by Sir Wilfrid Laurier's government. He follows the construction of the first trans-Canadian telephone line in the midst of the Great Depression of the 1930s and explains why, in the context of the Cold War, Canada built an electronic Great Wall of China in the far North. Rens examines the context that allowed the telecommunications industry to take hold so successfully in Canada and explores how the industry grew so quickly and managed to escape American domination. He situates Canadian accomplishments in telecommunications by comparing them with those of other countries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aTechnology & Engineering / Telecommunications.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356844040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773568440423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773568440/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-201